I think the fundamental and practical issue you're running into is that you're trying to make sense of a thought (division) with another thought (division). Divisions only teach you about divisions. Trying to learn about a division only creates more divisions in thought, which is to say, it makes you think more. Experience is already undivided and whole, dividing it (thinking about it) only teaches you about divisions (contents of thoughts/beliefs), not the whole experience. 

It's like trying to figure out what a painting looks like by cutting it into pieces and then examining the pieces. It just leads to endless dividing that never shows you the whole painting. 

If you stay with the initial thought/division, without trying to solve it with another thought, then you can examine the structure of the duality that the thought is proposing without turning it into smaller dualities to have a headache over. This is how you examine the "whole thing". Which is to say, first figure out if an outside or inside exists at all, before trying to figure out if things exist inside the outside or inside.

What you're doing is like someone who has a bunch of whiteboards laying around that they draw on. The initial whiteboard has a diagram of experience labelled "outside/inside". Then in order to "make sense" of that whiteboard, you lay out the aforementioned statements on the other whiteboards. What is missed is that all the whiteboards are inside your experience and that none of the divisions on them actually exist because they're whiteboards. You're essentially using experience to figure out if there isn't experience, so there isn't gonna be a certain part of experience that's more "correct" than the other.

To clarify how there is "one reality" or "one experience", the "twoness" of thoughts, like "outside and inside", are only ever implied, not actually experienced. "Outside" essentially means "not inside". "Up" essentially means "not down". "Right" means "not left". etc. etc.
